sec.p:
To reconstruct the participant’s estimated path from the angular response, we treated the reported heading angle θt (radians) as specifying the instantaneous lateral slope of the perceived trajectory at frame t. For each time step, we computed the incremental simulated forward displacement
(2)
Δzt=zt−zt−1, \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \Delta z_{t}=z_{t}-z_{t-1}, \tag{2} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
and converted the response angle into a lateral increment via
(3)
Δxt=tan⁡θtΔzt. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \Delta x_{t}=\tan \theta_{t} \Delta z_{t} . \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

The estimated lateral position was then obtained by forward integration starting from the initial position x0:
(4)
xt=x0+∑k=1ttan⁡θkΔzk. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x_{t}=x_{0}+\sum_{k=1}^{t} \tan \theta_{k} \Delta z_{k} . \tag{4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

We interpret the reported path as the output of a curl–driven feedback mechanism inspired by point attractor models used previously in steering control (Fajen and Warren, 2007; Wilkie and Wann, 2003a). Let θt denote the heading direction (direction of forward velocity in world coordinates) and ψt the gaze direction. We consider their difference
ϕt=ψt−θt \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \phi_{t}=\psi_{t}-\theta_{t}$$\end{document}
as a instantaneous heading error. The mean optic–flow curl ω¯t\begin{document}$\bar{\omega}_{t}$\end{document} is taken as a sensory measurement of this discrepancy, so that ϕt≈ω¯t/kc\begin{document}$\phi_{t} \approx \bar{\omega}_{t} / k_{c}$\end{document}, with kc being a curl–to–angle scale factor. This is motivated by the fact that curl increases whenever there is a discrepancy between θ and ψ. The observer controls heading by applying a yaw rate input ωt=θ˙t\begin{document}$\omega_{t}=\dot{\theta}_{t}$\end{document}:
(5)
θ˙t=ωt=Kpϕt≈Kpω¯tkc \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \dot{\theta}_{t}=\omega_{t}=K_{p} \phi_{t} \approx K_{p} \frac{\bar{\omega}_{t}}{k_{c}} \tag{5} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
so that positive curl induces a leftward turn (increasing θ) and negative curl induces a rightward turn. If gaze is held fixed (e.g. steady fixation), ψ˙t=0\begin{document}$\dot{\psi}_{t}=0$\end{document} and therefore
(6)
ϕ˙t=−θ˙t=−Kpϕt \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \dot{\phi}_{t}=-\dot{\theta}_{t}=-K_{p} \phi_{t} \tag{6} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

This is a simple first-order linear differential equation, and the heading error decays exponentially with a correction time constant 1/Kp:
(7)
ϕt=ϕ0e−Kpt \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \phi_{t}=\phi_{0} e^{-K_{p} t} \tag{7} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

This generates a predicted 2D path Ppred (Kp)={(zt,xt)}t=1T\begin{document}$P_{\text {pred }}\left(K_{p}\right)=\left\{\left(z_{t}, x_{t}\right)\right\}_{t=1}^{T}$\end{document} from the observed mean curl (ω¯)\begin{document}$(\bar{\omega})$\end{document} sequence. We then estimate Kp and forward velocity (v) as free parameters by minimizing a time-warped path discrepancy (J) using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW)(Giorgino, 2009) on the (z, x) sequences between the predicted and perceived paths:


J(Kp)=DTW(Pobs,Ppred(Kp))
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle J\left(K_{p}\right)=\operatorname{DTW}\left(P_{\mathrm{obs}}, P_{\mathrm{pred}}\left(K_{p}\right)\right)$$\end{document}



where


Pobs={(ztobs,xtobs)}t=1T
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle P_{\mathrm{obs}}=\left\{\left(z_{t}^{\mathrm{obs}}, x_{t}^{\mathrm{obs}}\right)\right\}_{t=1}^{T}$$\end{document}

In order to compare the different models, we employed information criteria adapted for distance-based model comparison. For each model, we computed a surrogate log-likelihood based on the normalized alignment cost:
log⁡L=−12(Dn) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \log \mathcal{L}=-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{D}{n}\right)$$\end{document}
where D represents the total DTW distance and n the number of observations, with D/n representing the average alignment cost per observation. This normalization ensures appropriate scaling for information criteria computation. We then computed the Akaike Information Criterion as:
AIC=2k−2log⁡L \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{AIC}=2 k-2 \log \mathcal{L}$$\end{document}
where k represents the number of parameters.

Visual motion is encoded by direction-selective units analogous to primate MT cortex, with 8 directional preferences:
(9)
Edirs=[cos⁡(θk),sin⁡(θk)]T,θk=2πk8,k=0,…,7 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \mathbf{E}_{\mathrm{dirs}}=\left[\cos \left(\theta_{k}\right), \sin \left(\theta_{k}\right)\right]^{T}, \quad \theta_{k}=\frac{2 \pi k}{8}, \quad k=0, \ldots, 7 \tag{9} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

To quantify the rotational (curl) component of optic flow around the current gaze position, we project local flow vectors onto the tangential direction of the circle centered at gaze. For each sampled location pi, we first compute its position relative to the gaze point g:
(11)
ri=pi−g \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \mathbf{r}_{i}=\mathbf{p}_{i}-\mathbf{g} \tag{11} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

This vector points from the gaze location to the sample point. The direction orthogonal to this vector corresponds to the local tangential direction of rotation around gaze. We obtain this unit tangential vector by rotating ri by 90° and normalizing:
(12)
t^i=[−ri,y,ri,x]T‖ri‖ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \hat{\mathbf{t}}_{i}=\frac{\left[-r_{i, y}, r_{i, x}\right]^{T}}{\left\|\mathbf{r}_{i}\right\|} \tag{12} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

Finally, the contribution of the optic flow at that point to local rotational motion is given by the projection of the flow vector vi onto this tangential direction:


ωi=vi⋅t^i
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \omega_{i}=\mathbf{v}_{i} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{t}}_{i}$$\end{document}

Positive values indicate counterclockwise motion around gaze, and negative values indicate clockwise motion. The mean curl is computed as follows:
ω¯=1Nused ∑i∈Sωi \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \bar{\omega}=\frac{1}{N_{\text {used }}} \sum_{i \in S} \omega_{i}$$\end{document}
where S represents samples satisfying ‖ri‖ > rmin after trimming outliers. In our implementation, Ntotal = 400 samples are drawn within a gaze-centered region.

Heading direction θ is represented by a ring attractor mechanism consistent with previous studies (Zhang, 1996), with neural activity x(ϕ, t) at preferred heading ϕ evolving as:
(13)
τdx(ϕ,t)dt=−x(ϕ,t)+∫W(ϕ,ϕ′)x(ϕ′,t)dϕ′+Iext(ϕ,t) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \tau \frac{d x(\phi, t)}{d t}=-x(\phi, t)+\int W\left(\phi, \phi^{\prime}\right) x\left(\phi^{\prime}, t\right) d \phi^{\prime}+I_{\mathrm{ext}}(\phi, t) \tag{13} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

We implement this dynamics by using a discrete ring of N = 181 units with preferred headings ϕj uniformly spaced between [−ϕmax, ϕmax]. The activity dynamics then follow:
(14)
xj[t+1]=xj[t]+Δtτ(−xj[t]+∑k=1NWjkxk[t]+Iext,j[t]) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x_{j}[t+1]=x_{j}[t]+\frac{\Delta t}{\tau}\left(-x_{j}[t]+\sum_{k=1}^{N} W_{j k} x_{k}[t]+I_{\mathrm{ext}, j}[t]\right) \tag{14} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

The external input Iext(ϕ, t) consists of two components:
(16)
Iext,j[t]=Igaze,j[t]+Iprior,j \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} I_{\mathrm{ext}, j}[t]=I_{\mathrm{gaze}, j}[t]+I_{\mathrm{prior}, j} \tag{16} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

The straight-ahead prior is:
(18)
Iprior ,j=I0⋅exp⁡(−ϕj22σp2) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} I_{\text {prior }, j}=I_{0} \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{\phi_{j}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{p}^{2}}\right) \tag{18} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
